{"/service/ndnp/nbu/batch_nbu_housesparrow_ver01/data/sn84020107/00517014679/1921010101/0374.xml":{"full_text":"FORECAST FOR\ni( 1921 BRIGHT\nBUSINESS DEPRESSION BEGIN\nNING TO DISSOLVE\nVIEWS OF PRICE EXPERT\nOptimistic Prediction of Govern\nment Officials and Business\nMen Is Based on Facts\nNow Developing\n'Washington, Jan. 1.\u2014Prosperity\nlike the (lowers ot the song will\nbloom In the spring. The business\ndepression Is already beginning to\ndissolve.\nThis, according to government of\nficials \u2019in the treasury, agriculture\nand labor departments, is the fore\ncast for 1921.\nIf true the forecast means an end\nof unemployment now involving\nhundreds of thousands of workers.\nIt also will end the great national\nbuying strike which swept the entire\ncountry early in the summer.\nEthelbert Stewart, government\nprice expert, believes the 1921 prices\nshould be far lower than those at\npresent.\n\"Business depression will disap\npear within a few weeks if manu\nfacturers and retail dealers will give\nup the idea that they can cling to\nwar prices,\u201d he said.\n\u201cThe buying public is in need of\nalmost every necessity. If prices\nwere reduced to a reasonable point\nthere would be a new rush of buy\ning, which would turn every factory\nwheel in the country and blot out\nunemployment almost immediately.\u201d\nThe optimistic prediction of gov\nernment officials and business men\nfor prosperity in the spring are bas\ned on facts now developing. Some of.\nthe factors are:\n1. Government receipts from\nluxury taxes have fallen far below\nthe figure of a year ago, indicating\nthe public has ended extravagant\nf buying.\nIWSfeafl W luxuries the public\nnow is buying stocks and bonds.\nLiberty bond transactions have been\nincreased for severr.i months.\n3. Food prices will descend to yet\nlower places in the first few months\nas the result of a bumper crop.\n4. Retail prices will undergo a\nsteady but sure decline, according to\nreports from fifty-five cities collect\ned by the labor department.\nThe pessimistic factors in the out\nlook 4re listed by government of\nficials as follows:\n1. Nearly 9,000 business failures\nin 1920 as compared with 6,400 in\nthe preceding year.\n2. Closing of scores,of factories\nin the textile and shoe manufactur\ning and. in automobije making cen\nters.\n-3. Falling prices of raw cotton\nand a general reduction in prices of\nall farni products including wheat,\ncorn and hogs.\n4. Unemployment.\nJobless workers now number 3,\n900,000 according to one unofficial\nestimate received here. Most gov\nernment officials, however, regard\nthis as an exaggerated estimate. Of\nficials of the labor board estimate\nthat unemployment now involves 1,\n000,000- workers.\nILLINOIS FARMERS\nTHROW MILK AWAY\nBecause of Oversupply and Poor Dc\nf inand It Is Poured into\nStreams\nEdwardsvillc, 111.. Jan. 1.\u2014De\ncreased consumption has\" left a large\nnumber of Southern Illinois milk\nproducers without a market, and\nthousands of gallons of milk are be\ning poured into rivers and creeks\ndaily. This announcement was made\ntoday by Fred Henke, a director of\nthe Southern Illinois Milk Producers\nAssociation, following a survey of\nthe milk situation\nMr. Henke asserted approximately\n2,000 farmers are unable to sell their\nmilk supply and that about 2,000\ngallons are poured into streams\nevery day. An average of 7,000 gal\nlons is fed to hogs daily, he added.\nThe situation results from the\noversupply, the cows producing more\nthan ordinarily at this season be\ncause of the warm weather, Mr.\nHenke said, and because several\nlarge condensaries have curtailed\ntheir output. Conditions are ex\npected to become better when the\nweather gets colder, he explained.\nThe producers have agreed to re\nduce the January price to St. Louis\ndistributors from $3.15 to $2.78 and\nthe distributors announced they\nwould reduce the retail price of pints\nfrom 10 to 9 cents in an effort to in\ncrease consumption.\n\"'\u2019A-'' f I;\nu\n\"\u20224'F :O'\"'1'-\u2019. tO\nINCORRIGIBLE YOUTHS\nHELD FOR ROBBERY\nRifled Market Store at Nebraska\nCity-\u2014Suspected of Iowa\nBurglaries\nAuburn, Nebr., Jan. 1.\u2014Two\nformer Nemaha county lads, Flex\nand Virgil Gillespie, are being held\nat Nebraska City, on the charge of\nrobbing the Markel store there re\ncently, and are wanted at Percival,\ni la., for a series of robberies of\nj stores at that place.\nFlex, the older of the boys, has\npractically confessed to the robbery\nof the Nebraska City store, feeling\nthat he would fare better with the\nmilder penalty imposed by the Ne\ni braska law, than he would that of\nthe \u201cHawkeye\u201d state,\nj It is alleged that after the rob\ni bery of the Markel store at Nebras\nka City the lads took their loot to\nSouth Omaha, where they peddled\nmuch of it. One of the boys was ar\nrested at Omaha and the other at\nCentral City.\nTwo-Cent Suit Against\nRock Island Sustained\nLincoln, Jan. 1.\u2014The two-cent\nfare law .passed in 1907 was held\nvalid and enforceable as against the\nRock Island railroad in Nebraska,\nin a report filed today in federal dis\ntrict court by John F. Stout, master,\nappointed to take testimony and\nmake findings.\nStout finds that on the propor\ntion of the property of the Rock Is\nland in Nebraska chargeable to pas\nsenger use, the road In the year\nending June 30, 1915, earned 10.14\nper cent. The court had enjoined\nthe railway commission from en\nforcing the law.\nThe case has been pending for\nyears and the set of figures used,\nrailroad officials contend, docs not\napply to present conditions.\n\nWages at Lumber Mills\nCut 15 to 25 Per Cent\nTacoma, Wash.. Jan. 1.\u2014Wage\ncuts of from 15 to 25 per cent in the\n-lumber mills of the northwest will\nbecome effective January 1, or when\nmills now closed are reopened, it was\nannounced here today by the local\nbranch of the Loyal Legion of Log\ngers and Lumbermen.\nThe wage reduction (.Will affect\ngjjcty thousand workmen*\nThe new scale is expected to be\nadopted by all mills, whether they\nare members of the loyal legion or\nnot.\nUnder the new scale, common la\nbor will be reduced from $4.40 to\n$3.60 a day and skilled labor will re\nceive a proportionate cut.\nLumber prices are at the lowest\nlevel in several years, manufacturers\ndeclared.\nMrs. A. Hinman of Wymore\nDies at Local Hospital\nMrs. A. Hinman, an old resident\nof Wymore, passed away Friday af\nternoon at a local hospital after a\nlingering illness, aged 71 years.\nThe family formerly lived on a\nfarm near Blue Springs, but later\nmoved to Wymore. Mrs. Hinman is\nsurvived by her husband and a\nnumber of children.\nThe remains were sent to Wymore\nj Saturday afternoon- over the Bur\nlington by W. W. Scott, undertaker,\nfor burial.\nelevator Destroyed by rire\nat Peru to Be Rebuilt\nJ The Farmers\u2019 elevator at Peru,\nj which was destroyed by tire a few\ndays ago, will be rebuilt. It was\nj th\u00bb property of the Farmers\u2019 Co\nOperative company and was built\nfour years ago.\nThe loss is placed at $12,000 with\n$10,000 insurance^ The fire is sup\nposed to have started from a defec\ntive flue.\nCardinal Gibbons Improved\nBaltimore, Jan. 1.\u2014Cardinal Gib\nbons was reported considerably im\nproved today after his relapse of\nThursday.\nThe cardinal is at the residence\nof Robert T. Shiver at Union Mills,\nMd., and it was said there was no\nimmediate cause for alarm. His ill\nness was reported due to a nervous\nbreakdown brought on by over ex\nertion. His mind is clear, it was\nstated.\nAnxiety is felt here however, and\nspecial prayers have been asked by\nBishop Cersignan.\nOnly Tailor\u2019s Dummy\nDenver. Jan. 1.\u2014 Fred\nAmick, a druggist called out\ntwo fire companies and the po\nlice when he saw the body of a\nwoman in the Platte river.\nAfter two police sergeants\nswam the river, the body\nturned out to be a tailor's\ndummy. \u2014ili?\nHARDING OPTIMISTIC\nBEGINNING NEW YEAR\nEconomic Questions Upper\nmost in Mind\u2014Big Plans\nFor Administration\nMarion, Ohio, Jan. 1.\u2014President\nelect Harding faced the opening of a\nnew year today confident that his\nadministration would bring back the\nnormal prosperity of the country,\nreduce taxes and establish a sound\nbusiness foundation.\nEconomic questions were upper\nmost in his mind today and he is\nlooking as much toward restoring\nthe sound economic conditions as to\nthe international league which con\nfronts him.\nIt was to obtain light on the situa\ntion and the prospect ot relief, that\nHarding called congressional leaders\nand financial experts to Marion.\nInformation obtained from them\nhas led the president-elect to believe\nthat under his administration the\nheavy burdens of war time taxes can\nbe diminished and that business con\nditions can be improved by sound ad\nministrative and legislative measures.\nHarding is informed by experts of\nthe federal reserve board that the\nmost difficult stage of the readjust\nment period has passed and that the\neconomic situation is sounder today\nthan it was a year ago.\nF. P. WICKHAM S NEWS\nSTAND BURGLARIZED\nThieves Get 20 Cents in Change,\nSome Cigarettes, Cigars and\nCandy\nThieves entered the news stand\nof E. P. Wickham on North Sixth\nstreet Friday night, and took the\n\u201chuge\u201d sum of 20 cents in change,\nwhich had been left in the cash reg\nister, some cigarettes, cigars and\ncandy.\nMr. Wickham was unable to state\nSaturday just how much was taken\nbut he is of the opinion that the\nthieves secured little for their\ntrouble.\nEntrance was gained to the store\nby unlocking the rear door. The\nburglary was reported to Chief of\nPolice Dillow, but at last reports no\nclue had been obtained to the guilty\nparties.\nCortland Basketball _\nTeam Trims College, View\nThe Cortland basketball team\ntrimmed the College View quintet at\nCortland Wednesday night by the\nscore of 39 to 19. The visitors were\noutplayed at every stage of the game.\nAs a preliminary bout, the Prince\nton team won from Hallam by the\nscore of 9 to 3.\nBurlington Op-erator\nat Wymore Married\nOperator R. L. McKissick of the\nWymore telegraph office was mar\nried to Miss Pearl Knabe of Nebras\nka City. Monday. Dec. 27,, and are\nnow on their honeymoon at McKit\ntrick. Mo. 1\nThey will return in about ten days\nand Mr. MsKissick will resume his\ntolegraph duties here.\u2014'Wymore\nDaily Arbor State.\n\u201cBob\u201d Finlay and Company\nMake Hit at Gilbert\n\"Bob\u201d Finlay ''and a bevy of\npretty girls staged a musical comedy\nat the Gilbert theatre New Year\u2019s\neve which was well worth the price.\nThe song hits and dances kept the\naudience in good humor throughout\nthe play, and the per/ormers were\nroundly applauded for their clever\nwork.\nAGENTS MAKE SMALL\nDENT IN CELEBRATION\nParties Wild as Ever, Says Cabaret\nand Cafe Managers of\nChicago.\nChicago, Jan. 1.\u2014Federal prohi\nbltion agents sponged the wet spots\noff Chicago as the city celebrated\nthe incoming of New Year\u2019s at mid\nnight.\nFifty revenue agents, divided into\nfive squads, visited many cabarets\nand lined the patrons up against the\nwall searching for hip liquor. Somd\nof the more noted cabarets, such as\nthe Green Mill Gardens, were visited.\nProprietors of places where liquor\nwas found were locked up. Scores\nof persons carrying liquor with them\nwere also held.\nHowever the prohibition agents\nwere able to make only a small (ident\nin Chicago's celebration. Police of\nficials were too busy keeping down\nholdups and other crimes to aid in\nthe mopping up and federal agents\nwere able to visit only a few places.\nIn practically all places parties\nwere as wild as ever, according to\nmanagers of cafes and cabarets in\nthe outlying districts. In the down\ntown district there' were few cele\nbrations and streets were deserted\nsoon after midnight.\nWhile the revelry was at its\nheight, watch^services were- being\nheld in many churches.\nI1 a v; .\"vy\nCRAB ORCHARD CASE\nPASSES INTO HISTORY\nCharge Against Ben Smith Ms\nmissed\u2014Girl Says She Lied\nAbout Uncle\nTecumseh, Jan, 1.\u2014The count:\ncourt was busy til afternoon Fri\nday in a hearing of the state vs\nBenjamin H. Smith, charged witl\naiding in the delinquency of a child\nThis case was the outgrowth oi\ncharges made In Omaha by hi!\nniece, Gladys Smith, who dteap\npeared in October and was later lo\ncated in Omaha and this week mar\nried here to Lester M. Reid, tha\nthe uncle was responsible for he:\nadmitted delicate condition.\nA number of witnesses were ex\namined, including an Omaha hote\nclerk and Roy Sampson.'Medera\nagent of that city. Mr. Sampson tes\ntified that the glrld told him a lone\nstory of alleged abuse by the uncle\nThe girl on the stand here today saic\nshe had lied to Mr. Sampson t(\nshield another. The evidence pro\nSliced by the state was not sufficient\nto hold the accused and the case wai\niismlssed-\nM\u2019KELVIE MAY HAVE\nTO FIGHT FOR CODI\nByrum of Franklin Will Tesl\nStrength in Speakership\nElection\nLincoln, Jan. 1.\u2014rAnti-McKelvh\nstrength in the lower legislative\nhouse may be put to its first test al\nthe caucus to be held Monday night\nwhen Byrum of Franklin will pu<\nhis candidacy for speaker befpre\nlower house republicans.\nByrum arrived in Lincoln yester\nday an avowed candidate for speak\ner and with his hip pocket bulging\nwith two anti-McKelvie bills.\nOne proposes to wipe out four o1\nthe department secretaries created\nby the governor\u2019s code bill of twe\nyears ago. The order would es\ntablish an entirely different budget\nsystem than that put into effect bj\nthe code bill.\n\u201cNo matter how the speakershii\ntight ends, 1 believe my two bills\nwill be laws when the legislature ad\njourns,\u201d Byrum si^d today.\n\u2022\u2018The fdht secretarfes vfhd\"\u00ab\u00a9oid\nbe abolished under the Byrum meas\nure are the secretary of the depart\nment of finance, secretary of the de\npartment of agriculture, secretary ol\ntrade and commerce and secretarj\npf public works. y\nByrum would place the stats\ntreasurer at the head of the depart\nment of finance, the commissionei\nof lands and buildings at the head\nof the department of agriculture\nthe secretary of state at the head ol\nthe department of trade and com\nmerce and the lieutenant governoi\nit the head of the department ol\npublic works.\nThe present status of the depart\nment of labor and department of ag\nriculture would remain the same\nis under the present code bill, ac\ncording to the Byrum bill. The sal\niries for the heads of these depart\nments would be $5,000 a year.\nByrum\u2019s budget bill provides for\nthe creation of a state budget com\nmission composed of a state treas\nurer, auditor of public accounts and\na state budget supervisor to be ap\npointed by a majority of the senate\nand house. The supervisor\u2019s duties\nwill consist of making tours of in\nspection of all institutions aided or\nmaintained by state money, investi\ngating expenditures and deciding\nan the amounts of future expendi\ntures.\nCaruso's Condition Satis\nfactory, Says Physician\nNew York, Jan. 1.\u2014Another con\nsultation of Enrico Caruso\u2019s phy\nsicians was called today. After this\nconference an official bulletin on\n;he tenor's condition will be issued.\nCaruso is \u201cdoing very nicely,\u201d Dr.\nHarowltz, his personal physician,\nsaid at 9 a. m.\nDeputy Sheriff Actqn\nLeaves Sheriffs Office\nF. W. Acton, representative-eleci\nfrom Gage county, has stepped down\nand out as deputy sheriff, and will\nleave Monday for Lincoln to take hit\nseat in the legislature.\nE. C. Salisbury of this city, whe\nwas appointed as his successor in the\nsheriff\u2019s office, will assume his duties\nat once.\nGabs New Strength\nChicago, Jan. 1.\u2014Improvement ol\nthe flour trade caused a new strengtt\nof wheat prices on the Chicago boarc\nof trade today. Trading had beer\nlight due to the holidays.\nTHE WEATHER\nFair tonight and probably\ncolder. 1\ni\nv V\nFARMERS SUPPORT\nANTI-SIRKE BILL\nProducers of Life\u2019s Necessi\nties Protest Against Alleged\n\u201cInherent Right\u201d\nWashington, Dec. 30.\u2014(Special\ncorrespondence.)\u2014That the Poin\ndexter anti-strike bill has the ardent\nsupport of farmers is demonstrated\nby a Statement made in behalf of a\nsimilar provision in the railroad bill\nlast spring. The statement referred\nto was signed by representatives of\nthe National Grange, the American\nFarm Bureau Federation, the Cotton\n1 States Board, and the Association of\nState Farmers\u2019 Union Presidents. It\nsays in part:\n\u201cSo much has been said in justi\nfication of the organized strike that\ni we deem it advisable to outline the\nposition of the farmers upon this all\nimportant question. We desire to\ndiscuss the question more particu\nlarly as applied to the railroads for\nthe reason that farmers are more\ndirectly affected by- railroad strikes\nthan strikes in other lines of indus\ntry or commerce.\ni \u201cThe statement has been made so\noften that organized workers have an\nInherent right to strike, that the pub\nlic generally has accepted the state\nment as being true and, as a result,\nstrikes have, in times past, received\nto some extent tne support oi puuuc\nopinion. Recent events, however, in\ndicate that the country is giving this\nquestion serious consideration, and,\nas a result, there is a growing de\nmand that some other method be em\nployed to bring about the settlement\nof controversies between employer\nand employe. This demand is more\nprohounced on the part of the farm\ners than of many other classes, for\nthe reason that they are affected\nmore directly than most other classes.\nThe farmers develop a section of\ncountry adopted to the production of\nperishable products. They spend\nvast sums of money In building\nhouses and barns, digging drainage\nor irrigation ditches, and in bringing\nthe land to a high state of productiv\nity. Such land could not have been\ndeveloped if the transportation fa\ncilities had not been such as to insure\nthat the farmers could get th'eir pro\nducts to market with the least pos\nsible delay and before they' become\nunfit for consumption.\n\u00ab*0*-\u00abre other h*nd\u00bb- \u00abo \u00ab*eat-eit#.\ncould be built *up i*nt were not for\nthe fact that those who live In them\nmay depend, first, on the farmers of\nthe country to produce an ample sup\nply of food and, second, on the rail\nroads to deliver farm products to\ncity consumers. with regularity and\nas needed.\n\u201cIt naturally follows that those\nwho believe that labor has an inher\nent right to organize a strike believe\nthat such organizations have a right\nto starve the people of the cities to\ndeath, on the one hand, and to de\nstroy the property of the farmers on\nthe other. No such right has ever\nexisted and no such right exists now.\nIt is economically unsound. What\nwould be the verdict of the people if\nthe farmers should suddenly decide\nto strike and refuse to supply the\nneeds of those who are not in a posi-,\ntion to produce food and clothing for\nthemselves? They would be con\ndemned from one end of the country\nto the other. If the farmers have no\nsuch moral br legal right, then why\nshould it be conceded by anyone that\nthose who handle their products\nducts have a right to block transpor\ntation and thus jeopardize the food\nand clothing supply of the nation?\nIf the farmers have no such rights,\nthose who handle his products have\nno such rights.\n\u201cThe farmers must look to con\ngress to -solve this great question in\nlight of fairness for all and not for\nthe benefit of the few, at the expense\nand perhaps misery and suffering for\nall.\u201d\nArgyle and Oscar Langdale re\nturned home Friday evening from\na two weeks\u2019 visit at Wakefield,\nNebr.\nMEXICANS HOLD FIVE\nAMERICANS AT SASABE\nSoldiers Are Arrested When They\nCross Border in Anto\nfor Water\nNogales, Ariz, Jan. 1.\u2014A party of\nfive American soldiers, under com\nmand of Lieut. H. H. Luther of the\ntopographic department of the army,\nwere taken into custody today by a\nparty of Mexican fiscal guards when\nthey motored across the international\nboundary line into Mexico at Sasabe,\nSonora. The soldiers were said to\nbe seeking water.\nThe prisoners were brought to\nNogales, where they were held for\nseveral hours in the municipal jail,\npending a conference between Ameri\ncan Consul Francis E. Dyer, Mexican\nConsul Monteverde and Lieut. Scott\nIsrael, army intelligence officer.\nThey were released on parole with in\nstructions to report in the morning\nto Mexican immigration officers,\npending an answer to a wire sent\nSecretary of War Callea at the City\nof Mexico for advice.\nBIG MEN WILLSmK TO\nORGANIZED AGRICULTURE\n\u25a04*'\nUnusually Strong Program\npared for Farmers' Meetings la^\nLincoln Next Week tfe\nLincoln, Jan. 1.\u2014The big event of\nthe annual meetings of the state\nagricultural associations in Lincoln\nJanuary 3rd to 7 th will be the joint;\nsession of all the organisations in the;\nLincoln city auditorium Wednesday\nafternoon. Governor McKelvie will\npr\u20ac*idp**at this meeting and among\nthe speakers will be .H. J. Waters,\neditor of the Kansas City Weekly\nStar, and an international figure in\nagriculture; and Secretary Craig of\nthe organisation promoting the deep\nwaterway from the Great Lakes to\nthe Atlantic ocean.\nMr. Waters was formerly dean of\nthe Missouri agricultural college and\npresident of the Kansas state agricul\ntural college. He was prominently\nmentioned for secretary of agricul\nture in President Wilson's cabinet\nand has been mentioned for the same\nposition in President-elect Harding\u2019s\ncabinet. The government sent him to\nthe Philippine islands to investigate\nagricultural conditions and he has\nlong been a prominent figure in agri\nculture.\nIn bringing the lakes-to-ocean pro\nject before the Nebraska farmers at\nthe annual meetings, the committee\niif charge of organized agriculture\nsays the loading of ocean-going ves\nsels at Chicago means a big thing to\nthe corn and wheat belt. It would\nplace the seaports within a thousand\nmiles of Nebraska farmers and re\nsult in'a material saving in freight\ncharges.\nThe meetings this year will be the\ntwentieth annual gatherings of the\nstate agricultural associations. Be*\ntween 3,000 and 5,000 farmers usual\nly attend. This is the first year the\nrailroads have granted reduced fares#\nand the committee in charge believes\nthat this, plus intense interest of\nfarmers in organization, will mean\nat least normal attendance.\nSeveral of the meetings this year\nare of unusual importance. The Ne\nbraska Farm Bureau Federation will\nmeet for the first time as an effective\norganization. It now represents be\ntween 40,000 and 50,000 farmers and\na campaign is under way to increase\nthe membership.\n'wo Hundred Acres Faded\nto Yield Twenty Bushels\nThere is one farmer in Nemaha\n...cpunty^aow^ J\ncorn this seasotf.'and^yet who'ls not\nbothering about the I&w frHce of\nthat king of grains.\nWhy is this thusly? *v ..s\nFor the good reason that he iet\nlike the pieman, met by Simple SI-'\nmon, he hasn\u2019t any.\nThe farmer in question is Glen\nMastin. There isn\u2019t a lazy bone in\nhis body and the lack of a crop was\nnot his fault.\nIt was entirely due to the cussed\nness of the Missouri river.\nGlen leased the land ana planted\nthe 200 a^pres to corn. He had a\ngood stand, but at the fatal mo\nment the river rose, submerged the\ngrowing crop, Thceded and left the\ncorn sickly and crippled. When har\nvest time came Glen bravely\nstarted to reap his sowing. After\nhe had gone oyer 20 acres and failed\nto get 20 bushels of nubbins he gave\nup in disgust.\nNext year he will farm in the vi- a\ncinity of Talmage, where he has\nprocured a good place.\u2014Auburn\n.Herald:\nFuneral o! Mrs. James\nFuneral services for the late Mrs.\nJames Leary will be held Monday\nmorning at 9:30 o\u2019clock from St.\nJoseph\u2019s Catholic church, conducted\nby by Father Bickert. Burial will be\nin the Catholic cemetery north of\nthe city.\nThe family requests there be no\nflowers.\nMonday Morning\nNew Mayor at Seward\nSeward, Jan. 1.\u2014C. T. Joern was\nmade mayor of Seward at a meeting\nof the city council last evening. Mr.\nJoern will complete the term of the\nlate Mayor George Ai Merrlam.\nWherry Case to Be\nDisposed of Monday\nCounty Attorney Vasey stated\nSaturday that he would probably\ndispose of the case of the state\nagainst Ralph Wherry, who was ar\nrested last week at Alma by Sheriff\nSchiek on the charge of passing two\nworthless checks in this city.\nWherry, who is 19 years of age,\nlives in West Beatrice, and it is\nalleged he left for Alma soon after\ncashing the checks.\nSnow at Alliance\nLincoln, Jan. 1.\u2014Reports\nhere at noon indicate that a\nheavy snow, which started fall\ning last night in Alliance and\nvicinity, was continuing. Snow\nwas reported at Ravenna dur- J\ning the morning accompanied,,/\nby a brisk northwest wind. Lin\ncoln experienced flurries during\nthe. day,\nr\ntli.\n\nGOVERNMENT/AGENTS T^K#0il\nto locateHush PRESIDENT\ny#:\nt\u00bbr\nWHEREABOUTS UNKNOWN\nSupposed to Have Landed Secrctcly\nin lire land front America\u2014\nW. \u25a0\u25a0\"\u2022JSL..\nltlsh Press Not Greatly\nExcited.'?<\n\u25a0\u25a0tit\nm\n111\nif\nv uxcueu. '^4 m\nDublin,>. Jan. 1.\u2014Government*-' f i\nagents today were engaged in a na-\ntion-wlde search for Eamonn Do\nValera, \u201cpresident of the Irish repub\nlic,\u201d<who is supposed to have landed^\nsecretly* in this country after a voy\nage from America.\nThe |rish office stated De Valera\nwas liable to he arrested as a* jail\nbreaker as he has been a fugitive\n\u00a3ince he escaped from prison ,\u2019n\nEngland. V However, the govern\nment\u2019s polity with regard to him has\nsot been formulated yet.\nt.\nThere was much speculation as- to\nhow be Valera managed to land*\nescretly in Ireland. There was a wide\nspread belief that he must have had\nsome lecret agreement with the\nBritish whereby he was permitted to\nenter tlis country.\nMilitary garrisons were on the\nilert today and commanders eV|\u00abrW*\niently believe that De Valera's Ar\nrival might excite Sinn Feiners to\ntresh outbreaks.\nm,\ns\n13\nQueenstown, the principal\u2019 Irish gM,\nport. has\"been strongly guarded torf .fc\nweeks, scf* it is assumed that 'be\nValery, did not land there. JPh\u00ab sur- vfcjjL\nmice is that he dropped off a steamer m\nIn Galway bay or on the west coast. Vs\n-rrrr.\nIW British Press'.Commends.\nLondon, Jan. 1.\n\nf \\y ''i\n-The British press\nha d\ntoday was not greatly excited at the\narrival of Eamonn De Valera, \u201cpres\nident of Ireland.\u201d Many newspapers\nemphasized the fact that the news\nwas fbased on the unsupported an\nnouncement of Harry Boland., Sinn\nFeiner, who styles himself as,, sec\nretary toll he president.\nThe Chronicle declared it\nlearned authoritatively,., tlkt Re;\nMVCTD iMflrTandod Jn I rent ndt\n\"The nws of his arrival should\ncause nvsurprise,\u201d said the Dally\nExpress; \u201cThe question is\u2014what'is\nlie there for?\u201d\nThev Dally News called attention\nto Sir Hpmar Greenwood's speech fa\nwhich he said:\n\u201cI honestly and sincerely say that\nthe Irish question is now rapidly\nloming to an amicable settlement. I\nrelieve that in six months there wilt\nbe two parliaments functioning in\nIreland,'opening the happiest chapter\nin the history of Ireland and the\nEnglish speaking world.\u201d\n;Vf\\J\nm\n*4\nt\n.\u2022-\u2022a:'\nCOMMISSION CLAIMED\nON REAL ESTATE DEAL i' V\nfohn A. Jeffreys Sues Nickel Invest\nment Company\u2014Other Court\nHouse Notes.\n\nm the sale of real estate from the\nNlckell Investment company, John\n\\.f Jeffreys has brought suit against\nthat corporation for the amount\nstated with interest at the rate of 7\nper cent from September 1, 1920.\nJeffreys says in 